24:54.287 --> 24:58.112
Texas A&M chapter is one of the local ways that now 
does educational presentations. We show films.

25:01.442 --> 25:02.223
We have discussions. We show films sometimes from 
both the anti-abortion and pro-abortion and have

25:02.283 --> 25:07.027
people discuss it. It's pretty hot sometimes. And 
in addition to education, now engages in

25:10.630 --> 25:26.125
petitions and letter writing and lobbying of 
state representatives and national senators and

25:10.630 --> 25:26.125
congresspeople. on that issue. They also have a 
legal defense and education fund, which helps

25:28.212 --> 25:45.157
provide legal and financial support to people who 
are involved in lawsuits, and I believe that now

25:28.212 --> 25:45.157
has supported several legal battles having to do 
with abortion rights. So it's active on a lot of

25:45.177 --> 25:53.749
fronts, trying to keep the option open for women to 
choose, and this is really important to

25:45.177 --> 25:53.749
understand that people are glorifying abortion 
in this movement at all or thinking about that's

25:54.016 --> 25:59.352
the best strategy of controlling pregnancy, but 
that women should have the choice. I was wondering

26:06.895 --> 26:16.904
if we could look at the feminist movements you 
point on reproductive rights and then get back to

26:06.895 --> 26:16.904
other issues that now holds. Would that be all 
right? Yeah. Okay. What are some, how does, there

26:20.066 --> 26:29.575
are two, first I would like to discuss the division 
in feminism that you were speaking of. There's a

26:29.555 --> 26:33.638
movement of radical feminism and then there's 
moderate, I believe. Is that correct? Well, yeah,

26:34.719 --> 26:38.923
there are different parts of feminists in this 
movement. Do they all hold the same viewpoint on

26:38.943 --> 26:42.466
reproductive rights? No. Yeah, they're not 
divided on most issues. Generally, there would be

26:47.330 --> 26:51.794
complete agreement on keeping abortion legal. 
What is the difference between individuals of the

26:52.154 --> 26:58.920
feminist movement today? I

26:59.525 --> 27:21.347
don't know if it's really as divided as the media 
presents it, because in general, the feminist

26:59.525 --> 27:21.347
movement is larger, now has a larger membership, 
and it's working more effectively than it ever has

26:59.525 --> 27:21.347
before to keep freedom of choice for women and to 
argue for other sexual harassment issues so it's

27:21.327 --> 27:46.457
not like a split ineffective movement and there 
actually were there was an editorial by sally

27:21.327 --> 27:46.457
quinn there's this writer for the washington post 
who said feminism is dead and we feminism isn't

27:21.327 --> 27:46.457
addressing the needs of the common women and women 
and that was like um responded to by joe ireland and

27:21.327 --> 27:46.457
people would know and basically say this is bull 
you know that feminism is going strong and you

27:21.327 --> 27:46.457
don't know what you're talking about ladies And 
it's true, it really is a big, strong movement. And

27:50.044 --> 27:52.026
there are a lot of internal splits. Historically, 
one split that was between maybe radical

27:52.046 --> 28:01.094
feminists and moderate feminists was over 
whether lesbians should be allowed to be members

27:52.046 --> 28:01.094
of NOW. And this occurred in the late 60s. Betty 
Friedan was against having lesbians be up front

28:04.477 --> 28:14.026
members of NOW and having a pro-lesbian or gay 
rights platform in NOW. She felt that that would

28:14.046 --> 28:16.748
give people more of a view that all feminists are 
lesbians, and that we couldn't afford as

28:17.082 --> 28:28.793
feminists to affiliate ourselves in this way, 
because that would lead to too much negative

28:17.082 --> 28:28.793
stereotyping. And what happened is, actually, 
there were many women in now, not the majority, but

28:29.313 --> 28:45.908
maybe a third or a fourth of the women who started 
now who were lesbians, and they felt enraged by

28:29.313 --> 28:45.908
this, and really hurt, like they had gotten the 
whole thing going, and supported Friedan, and

28:29.313 --> 28:45.908
done a lot of the work, and been out there on the 
front lines, and organized women's shelters and

28:46.225 --> 28:50.750
women's bookstores and now chapters. And then 
they were being told that they were not wanted in

28:51.270 --> 28:54.614
the organization. So they rose up and they formed 
this group called the Lavender Menace. They took

28:59.499 --> 29:04.484
over the stage at one of these conventions and they 
demanded that Nell's policy change. What

29:04.565 --> 29:13.414
happened is Nell did reject the lesbian members 
for several years and then its policy was changed

29:04.565 --> 29:13.414
and lesbians rejoin now. So predominantly the 
membership is, you know, pretty heterosexual,

29:13.799 --> 29:36.065
but there's probably maybe less than a fourth, 
maybe a tenth of the membership, or some portion,

29:13.799 --> 29:36.065
maybe no more than the population proportion, 
maybe a tenth to a fifth are lesbians, because

29:13.799 --> 29:36.065
lesbians tend to have a feminist awareness 
because they're already oppressed in terms of

29:13.799 --> 29:36.065
their sexual orientation. They also tend to share 
the value of feminism, it'd be kind of nuts not to.

29:41.944 --> 29:42.064
Right. For them not to. So that was one division, 
but that's kind of like now, you know, we have an

29:43.027 --> 29:51.433
openly bisexual president of now, Joe Ireland. 
has come out, she was brought out, but she has

29:51.667 --> 30:01.317
publicly come out as having a female lover and 
still being married to her husband, who she loves

29:51.667 --> 30:01.317
very much and has been very supportive. So, you 
know, best of both worlds, I guess. I don't know how

30:04.280 --> 30:10.807
she does it, but she's been accepted, and people 
knew this about her and voted her in anyway. So that

30:11.227 --> 30:20.897
division is by the wayside, and the only other 
division I can think of is the one over

30:11.227 --> 30:20.897
pornography, and that's not so much between 
moderate and radical feminists, because even

30:11.227 --> 30:20.897
among radical feminists, There's division. Some 
of them are saying women should have all kinds of

30:22.399 --> 30:37.033
pornography available to them, and that we are 
trying to protect women from sexuality in a way

30:22.399 --> 30:37.033
that's actually demeaning, that women are old 
enough, they're mature enough to make their own

30:22.399 --> 30:37.033
decisions, and blah, blah, blah. And we don't want 
the government to censor more materials. And then

30:41.177 --> 30:43.740
the other group is the Dworkin McKinnon group. But 
that's really a split throughout. all feminists

30:46.358 --> 30:49.583
about what to do with pornography. So I wouldn't 
characterize there really being a radical

30:49.783 --> 30:55.751
feminist versus moderate feminist split. Do you 
feel that the feminist viewpoint on pornography

30:55.771 --> 31:04.884
will be given legislative attention as has been 
done in Canada now? Eventually, I think it will.

