31:41.823 --> 31:49.713
definitely the Canadian precedent is something 
that people are going to take and try to encourage

31:41.823 --> 31:49.713
to happen in the United States. I'd say it probably 
will take at least another 10 years, at least. It's

31:53.116 --> 31:57.463
a very hard fight because there's so many economic 
interests. And I mentioned in class that the

31:57.483 --> 32:13.709
American Booksellers Association, which is 
Hastings and Wallen Books and all these huge

31:57.483 --> 32:13.709
corporations who profit from selling magazines, 
pornography magazines, don't want any control on

31:57.483 --> 32:13.709
that stuff because they'll lose millions of 
dollars in profits. So they're funding the battle

32:13.729 --> 32:16.493
against. It's not just pornographers. It's like 
anybody else who benefits from it. I was going to

32:21.179 --> 32:28.690
ask you about NOW and the correlation between NOW 
and the feminist movement. Is NOW the only tool

32:28.710 --> 32:33.737
that the feminist movement has? No, it's the 
largest national organization, but there's

32:34.178 --> 32:39.946
another one that Ellie Smeal started. She was a 
former president of NOW, two presidents ago. She

32:43.271 --> 32:50.562
started an organization called Feminist 
Majority, which funds candidates for office.

32:50.997 --> 32:58.340
women candidates and actually helped fund a lot of 
the women who ran for senator and representative

32:50.997 --> 32:58.340
this time around. And she believes, Ellie 
believes that The only way women are going to

33:01.730 --> 33:07.256
really be able to change the system is to get 
elected to office. We've got to put priority on

33:07.516 --> 33:09.218
that. So there's that organization. Many people 
are members of both. I think I'm a member of both. I

33:13.742 --> 33:16.826
know I'm a member of now, and I think I've paid my 
dues to the other one this year. There's also

33:18.007 --> 33:25.915
specific abortion rights groups like National 
Abortion Rights Action League, NERA. that's

33:26.333 --> 33:31.017
focused on just, you know, keeping abortion 
legal, and there are state divisions of that.

33:31.037 --> 33:35.521
There's Terol, which is a Texas abortion rights 
action league. Other feminist groups... There's

33:38.544 --> 33:48.032
another one that's just started called the Third 
Party or something, and it's like to get a third

33:38.544 --> 33:48.032
political party that would be more responsive to 
the needs of women in minority groups. I think

33:48.373 --> 33:51.295
that's another separate feminist organization. 
But now it's really the biggest. Okay. Um... What

33:55.544 --> 34:04.626
got you interested in teaching sexual behaviors?

34:07.576 --> 34:14.042
Just in, I guess it wasn't an interest, it was my 
role when I applied to be a tenure track professor.

34:14.062 --> 34:25.614
I'd already, I'd been allowed to teach some 
courses as an assistant professor who was

34:14.062 --> 34:25.614
visiting, but I hadn't taught the sex course yet 
because the person I was working with, who was my

34:14.062 --> 34:25.614
senior, taught the sexuality course here. And so I 
just, it was part of the role I was hired for to teach

34:25.634 --> 34:33.181
that particular course. And I knew immediately 
that it would be a wonderful course to teach. And

34:37.208 --> 34:55.666
the challenge for me was to teach it in a way that 
gave the students the basic information that's in

34:37.208 --> 34:55.666
the text, but also gave them more of a critical 
awareness that this isn't the only information,

34:37.208 --> 34:55.666
that there are different points of view, that this 
is still a social construct that we need to be aware

34:37.208 --> 34:55.666
of, the point of view of the researchers. And it's 
hard to do that with an undergraduate class,

34:55.686 --> 35:01.672
because it would be easy to talk about people's 
heads. But it seems to me the students really do get

35:02.072 --> 35:05.916
the idea after a while. understand why some of the 
readings are there. The only way to do that is to

35:09.401 --> 35:17.192
have this huge amount of reading, to have the 
textbook and to have these articles which give

35:09.401 --> 35:17.192
different points of view on the side. Do you feel 
more in any way gratified that you're doing, that

35:18.133 --> 35:30.891
you are educating undergraduate students on this 
subject in what has been a traditional

35:18.133 --> 35:30.891
conservative school? Yeah, I really do. I didn't 
think about that when I started, but I really soon

35:32.434 --> 35:57.148
became aware that the person who teaches that sort 
of a course, probably anywhere, but especially

35:32.434 --> 35:57.148
maybe a place like Texas A&M, that they're 
addressing a need for information that has not

35:32.434 --> 35:57.148
been addressed for many of these students before, 
and that so many of the students in my classes come

35:32.434 --> 35:57.148
and talk to me after class, or they'll come in and 
shut the door, and they'll say, right, this

35:57.128 --> 36:26.646
happened to me or I have a question and they've 
never been able to ask anybody before and I realize

35:57.128 --> 36:26.646
that there is an atmosphere of trust that happens 
in that class and that's very important and that I

35:57.128 --> 36:26.646
can help individual students as well as teaching 
these ideas and in terms of challenging

35:57.128 --> 36:26.646
traditional beliefs I do think that the class 
succeeds in doing that and that it opens people to a

35:57.128 --> 36:26.646
different point of view that I don't think that 
they would have gotten exposure to I know if I was

36:26.795 --> 36:39.454
teaching this course in New York or California 
where I'm from, I would just sort of be like, oh,

36:26.795 --> 36:39.454
yeah, yeah, yeah, you know, we know that, and I 
would just sort of be like, you know, like a lot of

36:26.795 --> 36:39.454
other profs there, and the students would They're 
not all completely educated and liberated, but

36:39.957 --> 36:43.402
they would have more of an idea. And now here I feel 
almost like a missionary in a strange place. I'm

36:48.590 --> 36:54.900
speaking these things like, oh, women have equal 
rights, and people are all freaked out. And I'm

36:54.920 --> 36:57.283
saying, no, women are sexual too. And I can see some 
of the guys shifting around going, women aren't

36:57.484 --> 37:01.970
sexual. We're just supposed to lie there. And I 
don't think anyone would say that, but... I think

37:07.447 --> 37:13.997
that some people come in with those kinds of 
attitudes, and I can tell that people are thinking

37:07.447 --> 37:13.997
a lot about the course. And I've had students come 
up to me later, like years later, and say, wow, that

37:14.017 --> 37:22.269
course was really a good course, and it really made 
me think, and it's really helped me in my

37:14.017 --> 37:22.269
relationships. And that's important to me. In a 
nutshell, what would you say your teaching

37:24.973 --> 37:31.322
strategy was for the class? What is the class 
about?

37:37.923 --> 38:04.977
The goal of the course, the objective, is to help 
students to have a critical understanding of

37:37.923 --> 38:04.977
sexuality, meaning an understanding of how 
sexuality is created in our society, where it

37:37.923 --> 38:04.977
comes from, where our ideas and beliefs come from, 
and a greater appreciation for the malleability

37:37.923 --> 38:04.977
of sexuality, that even if you're brought up in a 
certain way, that there are many other people who

38:05.260 --> 38:08.946
believe very differently. And maybe an 
understanding of cultural differences and an

38:09.246 --> 38:26.432
appreciation for people who are different 
sexually, like gay and lesbian individuals, an

38:09.246 --> 38:26.432
understanding of people who are gender 
dysphoric, rather than just a condemnation or

38:09.246 --> 38:26.432
prejudice, to understand what might make 
somebody feel this way. So I guess creating

38:27.874 --> 38:34.204
greater awareness and understanding of 
sexuality for themselves and for their people.

